"I never tasted better pork. . . we have a good frame house with five glass windows" (Box 186, folder 3317). The family's apparently successful adjustment to life in America can be traced throughout the correspondence.

Other Boswells also includes a list of tacks on Auchinleck lands in 1932, "Particulars of the Estate of Auchinleck," and "Plans of the Estate." These last are from an undated sales offering and provide much useful detail about the later history of the barony lands.

The second section, Related Papers , contains a variety of material either collected by the lairds of Auchinleck or concerning families connected to them. Included are a commission signed by Mary Queen of Scots and sealed with her Great Seal; a group of charters pertaining to the Bonar of Rassy family; and a debt progress of the Primroses of Rosebery, perhaps related to the Bruce family. The Campbells of Loudoun are represented by a charter, a lawsuit against Cunningham of Craigends, and documents concerning disputes over teinds (Box 186, folder 3336 and Box 194, folder 4029).

Memorabilia which could not be assigned definitely to a specific laird have been placed in Box 187, folders 3345-51. These include a small painting on wood of Moses striking the rock, possibly eighteenth-century; a scrap of beadwork; and a broken example of the Great Seal of Richard Cromwell. Printed items consist of a 1732 catechism and several titles dealing with the Presbyterian "Synods" controversy of the 1730s and 1740s.

There are also three folders of writings in this section. "Ane meditasione for wakning the secur sowle" is a religious exercise in a mid or late seventeenth-century hand. An analysis of political conditions throughout the world, with special reference to the future of Great Britain, is offered in "Universal Politics; or, the Politics of Reason and Good Sense." It was composed around 1785, and the author devotes much attention to "recent events in the former Colonies," claiming to have spent four years in Nova Scotia and to have conversed with Samuel Adams, George Washington, and other American figures. He is possibly the Rev. William Doyle, whose "Universal Religion; or, the Religion of Reason and Good Sense" is found in Series II of Part I (Box 21, folder 481).

Other items of interest in this section are instructions by Queen Elizabeth to Sir John Fortescue, a portion of an unidentified proclamation by King James VI, and a recipe book containing entries in various eighteenth and nineteenth century hands concerning such topics as lotion for chapped skin, "India pickle," and "good Civet." Box 188, folder 3363 holds an undated and highly decorated "Supplicatio ad Papam" of doubtful authenticity.

Other papers consists of legal documents with no apparent connection to any of the lairds or the land progresses. Most of them are eighteenth-century and may have become separated accidentally from the "Bundles" of James Boswell, writer in Ayr. They have been grouped by type of document and arranged alphabetically by type and chronologically within each type. The series concludes with eighteen folders of "wrappers." These are documents or scraps of documents which were used as covers for bundles of other papers. Many of these are vellum, and some contain much early text, although others have been scraped or damaged. An attempt has been made to file the more intact vellum examples first, followed by the less interesting items.

odd.head: APPENDIX I: GENEALOGICAL CHARTS OF RELATED FAMILIES
odd.p: The first chart, BOSWELLS OF FIFE, contains information on the direct ancestors of the first laird, Thomas Boswell. The following charts document several branches of the Auchinleck family and are arranged by generation of separation. Finally, charts are included for two closely related families, the Bruces and the Cochranes of Ochiltree.

The collateral lines are often poorly documented, particularly for the seventeenth century, and these charts should be considered guides research rather than definitive genealogies. Each family has been followed from its foundation (when possible) to the last generation whose members are documented in the Boswell Collection.

The number of marriages between cousins in the Boswell families means that the researcher should be prepared to consult as many as three different tables for complete information. An asterisk preceding an entry indicates that additional information can be found on another chart.

The information is drawn from a variety of sources, the unpublished manuscript of Volume 2 of Jasper John Boswell's unpublished History and
Genealogical Tables of the Boswells and the papers in the Boswell Collection. In cases of contradiction among sources, the primary source was always preferred.

odd.head: Appendix II: Glossary of Scots and Legal Terminology
odd.p:
This glossary has been compiled from several sources, including the Oxford English Dictionary and John Dalrymple's Essay Toward a General
History of Feudal Property . It is not intended to be a complete list of Scottish words or feudal law terminology, and the definitions are not exhaustive. Rather, it is a guide to some of the unfamiliar words appearing frequently in the papers of the Boswell Collection.

backbond A document by which a person receiving or holding a seemingly absolute title to property acknowledges that he is actually holding it in trust for a specified reason, and binds himself to return it or account for it after that purpose is served. The true owner of the property is usually the grantor of the absolute deed and the grantee of the backbond.
barony In Scotland, a large freehold estate, almost always held directly from the King; the owner is called the laird , which is not a title of nobility but "goes with" the land.

bond Generally, a legal document by which a person binds himself, his heirs, executors, or assigns to pay another person or his representatives a sum of money. There are many types of bonds in Scottish law, including the backbond and the heritable bond .
cain, kain Rent payment in kind made by tenants to a feudal superior.

clare constat Latin for "It is clearly established," meaning that the feudal superior is satisfied that his late vassal died enfeoffed in the land, and that the person claiming entry into his estate is the nearest lawful heir. A precept
of clare constat is a deed executed by a superior in order to complete the title of his vassal's heir to the lands held by the dead vassal.
composition Specialized meaning: fee paid to be admitted as a burgess.
dispone To make over or assign property legally and formally, usually by means of a disposition .
distreyne Distrain: to seize goods or property in order to enforce payment of debt.
entry Entry into possession or occupation of lands, especially the act of taking possessing of lands by setting foot on them ("entering" them.) See also non-entries .

escheat In English feudal law, the lapsing of land to the Crown on the death of an intestate tenant or owner without heirs. In Scottish law, escheat has a wider sense, including confiscation or forfeiture of property at law (e.g. upon conviction of treason). A simple escheat is an absolute forfeiture; a liferent escheat is forfeiture of all profits accumulated during the forfeited person's lifetime.
excambion Exchange or barter, particularly of land

feu Estate in land held on condition of homage and service to a superior lord, by whom it is granted and in whom ownership remains (English fee). Or, a feudal tenure of land in which the vassal substitutes an amount of grain or money for military service. In modern usage, a perpetual lease at a fixed rent.
feu simple Estate in land which belongs to the owner and his heirs perpetually, not limited to any particular class of heirs.
fiar Owner of the feu simple of a property. See also: life-rent .
fiars The annually fixed prices of different kinds of grains.
grassum Fine paid to a feudal superior when making entry into a feu .

heritable bond Bond for a sum of money, the security for which is a conveyance of land out of heritage to be held by the creditor until the debt is paid. A heritable security is usually created by enfeoffing the creditor in the lands conditionally, i.e. in case of non-payment. Many of the title transfers in Land Purchases and Land Records are actually executions of Heritable bonds and/or backbonds .
heritors Literally, owners of heritable property; usually refers to men who owe the "parish" or "public" burdens (minister's salary, road taxes, etc.).
horning Outlawing. By the seventeenth century, an action against a delinquent debtor issued under the signet, charging him to pay or "be put to the horn" (declared rebel).
intromit To interfere with property belonging to another person.

laird A Scottish landowner who holds land directly from the Crown; a tenant-in-chief of the King. Not a title of personal nobility. A laird is referred to by the name of his holding; the current holder of Auchinleck is referred to as Auchinleck.

liferent Income a person is entitled to receive for life, or the right to receive that income. Often granted in marriage provisions for widows; usually reserved by the holder of a feu if he transfers title to the feu itself before his death.
mains The "main" farm of an estate, usually farmed by the laird directly rather than feued.
master In the phrase "Master of" followed by the name of a land holding (e.g. "Master of Auchinleck"): the eldest son and heir presumptive of the laird of that land.

non-entry Failure of an heir to enter land and to obtain investiture in it from his feudal superior. Non-entries are the feudal fines arising from this failure. Most often seen as a "gift of the non-entries" (i.e., a remission of the fines) by a superior to the heir.
outquyt To free lands from a wadset by paying the debts upon them.

poind To seize and sell the goods of a delinquent debtor. Usually seen as part of a "writ of horning and poinding," ordering the debtor to make restitution or to be declared outlaw and forfeit his goods.

progress In progress of the writs , means "such a series of title- deeds of a landed estate as is sufficient in law to constitute a valid and effectual title thereto." The best documentation consists of sasines and charters, but many other types of legal instruments may be found in them.
rase, raise To draw up a legal summons, letter, etc.
resignation Form by which holder of a feu returns it to the hands of the feudal superior and/or transfers title of a heritable feu to the next heir.

reversion Obligation by a creditor which allows that his debtor may redeem land in which he had enfeoffed the creditor as security. Usually found in combination with heritable
bonds , backbonds , and/or wadsets .

sasine As a verb, the act of giving possession of feudal property. An instrument of sasine is the legal document that records and proves a transfer of property, and is the decisive proof of ownership in Scottish law. After 1614 all sasines were required to be registered in the Book of Sasines.

service Procedure for determining who is the heir to a dead person. A general service determines who is the heir to someone generally, while a special service discovers the heir to a particular estate. A retour is the report of the inquest in a particular service, with the jury's verdict, and these are either general or special also.
sucken The group of tenants in thirlage to a particular mill, required to bring their grain to it and to keep it in repair.
tack Lease for a specified period of time. Usually applied to farms and land property, but liferents , teinds , and other forms of income can also be leased.
tailzie An entail, binding the descent of a property through a specified line of heirs.

teinds Tithes. Originally owed to parish churches, after the Reformation the right to collect these was often sold to the heritors of the parish or other notables. The 1633 Act of Teinds was an attempt to regularize the situation.
thirlage Being bound, as a tenant, to bring one's grain to the landlord's mill and to keep that mill in repair.
tocher Dowry agreements and the dowry itself.

wadset Type of mortgage in which title to land is conveyed as security for a debt, with an explicit reservation of power by the debtor to recover the lands if the debt is paid (usually within a specified period).
writer Counterpart of the English "solicitor." Lawyer who can advise clients and prepare causes, but who is not allowed to present them at the Bar.
w.s. Abbreviation for "writer to the Signet," the highest classification of writers .
